======================================================================
THE (2,3,5) UNIVERSE — COMPLETE SESSION S79 SYNTHESIS
======================================================================

======================================================================
PART 1: THREE BOUNDARIES AT n=10
======================================================================

BOUNDARY 1: Tournament Count > Symmetry Count
  T(n) = 2^C(n,2), n! = |S_n|
  T(n)/n! crosses 1 (downward) at n=1 (trivially)
  T(n)/n! > 1 FIRST at n=3 (T=8 > 6)
  But the GROWTH RATE crosses: C(n,2) > n·log₂(n) at n≈10

  n= 3: T(n)/n! =           1.33
  n= 4: T(n)/n! =           2.67
  n= 5: T(n)/n! =           8.53
  n= 6: T(n)/n! =          45.51
  n= 7: T(n)/n! =         416.10
  n= 8: T(n)/n! =        6657.63
  n= 9: T(n)/n! =      189372.46
  n=10: T(n)/n! =     9695869.73
  n=11: T(n)/n! =   902597327.92

BOUNDARY 2: Petersen Graph
  K(5,2) has 10 = C(5,2) vertices
  10 = KEY₁ · (KEY₁+KEY₂)
  Unique Kneser graph: smallest non-complete K(n,2)
  K(4,2) = K₃ (complete, trivial)
  K(5,2) = Petersen (first interesting)

BOUNDARY 3: (2,3,5) Spherical Condition
  1/p + 1/q + 1/r > 1 for polyhedra
  (2,3,5): 1/2+1/3+1/5 = 31/30 > 1 ✓
  (2,3,7): 1/2+1/3+1/7 = 41/42 < 1 ✗
  The LAST spherical triple is (2,3,5)
  Excess: 31/30 - 1 = 1/30 = 1/h(E₈)

CONVERGENCE:
  All three boundaries involve the number 10:
  • T(n)/n! becomes exponentially large around n=10
  • K(5,2) has exactly 10 vertices
  • The (2,3,5) triple gives 2·5 = 10
  And they are CONNECTED:
  • f(10) = 56 = T(6) = dim(V_E₇)
  • The Petersen complement has 30 = h(E₈) edges
  • The spherical excess 1/30 inverts to h(E₈)

