======================================================================
PART 3: THE COXETER NUMBERS AS A RECURRENCE
======================================================================

Coxeter numbers of exceptional groups:  [6, 12, 12, 18, 30]

  Can {6,12,12,18,30} be expressed as A·2ⁿ+B·3ⁿ?
  Ratios: 12/6 = 2  12/12 = 1  18/12 = 3/2  30/18 = 5/3  
  Ratios: 2, 1, 3/2, 5/3
  = KEY₁, 1, KEY₂/KEY₁, (KEY₁+KEY₂)/KEY₂

  The ratio pattern: 2, 1, 3/2, 5/3
  These are Fibonacci-like: each ratio ≈ next Fibonacci ratio
  1/1, 2/1, 3/2, 5/3, 8/5, ...
  The Coxeter number ratios FOLLOW THE FIBONACCI FRACTIONS!

  Fibonacci convergents to φ:
    F_2/F_1 = 2/1 = 2.000000
    F_3/F_2 = 3/2 = 1.500000
    F_4/F_3 = 5/3 = 1.666667
    F_5/F_4 = 8/5 = 1.600000
    F_6/F_5 = 13/8 = 1.625000
    F_7/F_6 = 21/13 = 1.615385

  OBSERVATION: the ratios h(X_{i+1})/h(X_i) use
  successively better rational approximations to φ:
    h(F₄)/h(G₂) = 2/1 = F₃/F₂ (above φ)
    h(E₆)/h(F₄) = 1/1 = F₂/F₂ (below φ)
    h(E₇)/h(E₆) = 3/2 = F₄/F₃ (above φ)
    h(E₈)/h(E₇) = 5/3 = F₅/F₄ (below φ)
    (hypothetical E₉ would need h(E₉)/h(E₈) ≈ 8/5 = F₆/F₅)
    But E₉ doesn't exist! The sequence terminates at (2,3,5).

  Product of ratios: 2·1·(3/2)·(5/3) = 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂
  = h(E₈)/h(G₂) = 30/6 = 5 ✓

